<HEAD>Sugar Shock Strikes at Candy Wholesalers' Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shortly after noon on the <DATE>second day of the</DATE>
<ORGANIZATION>National Candy Wholesalers Association</ORGANIZATION>'s summer convention, sugar
shock hit and the guy in the big M&amp;M costume started to look fuzzy.
   No thanks, no mas, enough already. No more chocolate bars,
gumdrops, gumballs, rock candy, licorice sticks, fudge, toffee
crunch, jelly beans, peppermint creams, caramel-coated popcorn,
<ORGANIZATION>Moon Pies</ORGANIZATION> or Mellow-Munchies.
   Take away your heart-shaped <ORGANIZATION>Valentine</ORGANIZATION>'s Day boxes, your Count
Dracula treats for Halloween, your chocolate Easter bunnies. Get
thee hence, Garbage Can-dy, <ORGANIZATION>Heavenly Passion</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Pee-Wee</ORGANIZATION>'s
Playhouse Fun Paks.
   Glucose levels were going through the roof of the <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>
Convention Center when the semiannual confab of 6,500 candy
wholesalers got into full swing <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. At midday, sales people
began tempting passersby with heaps of sweets, chewing gum and
munchies at 630 booths covering the floors of two large exhibition
halls.
   Other conventioneers swarmed through the ``sample room'' filling
small paper tote bags with goodies while a tape-recorded voice
repeatedly urged guests to exercise restraint. ``Thank you, and
have a sweet tooth,'' the voice said.
   The hottest items on the market this year seem to be gummy bears
_ a chewy confection long popular among European children _ upscale
``gourmet'' chocolates from such exotic locales as <LOCATION>Belgium</LOCATION>, and
bubble gum that looks like pizza, served in a tiny Domino's Pizza
box.
   For the health-conscious, there is tofu chocolate (``non-dairy,
no white sugar, no cholesterol''), granola bars and ``high-fiber''
candies coated with yogurt.
   For those who don't care, there are white chocolate lollipops in
the shape of big-bosomed blondes and ``shelf-stable'' cotton candy
in cardboard <LOCATION>Ringling Bros.</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Barnum &amp; Bailey</ORGANIZATION> circus wagons.
   Licorice comes in vines, ropes and twists. Popcorn comes in
barbecue, nacho and jalapeno flavors. Kids' candies come in toy
light bulbs, water pistols, skeletons, skulls, rockets, whistles,
snakes, UFOs, spaceships and parachute jumpers.
   Two of the oldest candy brands in <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> _ both introduced in
<DATE>1912</DATE> _ are still on the market, according to industry historians.
They are the Nut Goodie bar, made by <PERSON>Pearson</PERSON>'s of <ORGANIZATION>St. Paul</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Minn.</LOCATION>,
and the Goo Goo Cluster manufactured by <ORGANIZATION>Standard Candy Co.</ORGANIZATION> of
<LOCATION>Nashville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tenn</LOCATION>.
   Association president <PERSON>Ernest D. May</PERSON>, a candy packager and
distributor from <LOCATION>Grove City</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pa.</LOCATION>, said the <MONEY>$9.6 billion</MONEY> candy
business is growing steadily after a slump in the <DATE>1970s</DATE> caused
partly by high sugar prices and a stagnant population in the
biggest candy-buying age bracket, 15 to 30.
   Consumption had risen to <MONEY>19.3 pounds</MONEY> of candy per capita last
year, and <DATE>May</DATE> says the wholesalers' goal is 25 pounds for every
American man, woman and child by <DATE>1995</DATE>.
   ``It's a real challenge but I think it's reachable,'' <DATE>May</DATE> said
in an interview. ``The future is bright.''
   After gummy bears, what fantastic new candy treat is next?
   ``If I could answer that,'' he replied, ``you and I could both
retire.''
</TEXT>
