<HEAD>It's Only Puppy Love</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every dog has its day, and a <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> retailer is
hoping that day is <ORGANIZATION>Valentine</ORGANIZATION>'s Day.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Tokyu Department Store</ORGANIZATION> is going all out this year to make
sure its pet-owning customers have a vast array chocolates,
cookies, fish sausages and other drool-inducing delicacies to
choose from.
   ``I'm buying chocolates for my boyfriend, so why not for my
dog?'' said <PERSON>Ayako Endo</PERSON>, a 22-year-old office worker.
   Miss <PERSON>Endo</PERSON> said buying a <MONEY>$3.50</MONEY> gift set of goodies was the least
she could do for her 12-year-old English setter.
   ``They're good,'' she said. ``I eat them too.''
   As in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, Japanese celebrate <ORGANIZATION>Valentine</ORGANIZATION>'s Day by
giving sweets to a loved one. <ORGANIZATION>Tokyu</ORGANIZATION> is hoping to expand the concept
a bit to include animals.
   ``We've been selling the chocolates for about three years, but
this is the first year we have gone all out,'' said <ORGANIZATION>Tokyu</ORGANIZATION> pet shop
clerk <PERSON>Yoshiko Kashiwazaki</PERSON>, pointing to a large table covered with
heart-shaped gift sets wrapped in red-and-yellow ribbons.
   A poster showed two furry creatures cuddled up over the slogan:
``For Lovers, Sweet Valentine.''
   ``I love you only,'' said one. ``Me too,'' replied the other.
   Shoppers are eating up the idea.
   ``I just love cats and dogs,'' said 12-year-old <PERSON>Yuki Kuwahara</PERSON>,
who bought a chocolate and chew-bone gift for a Maltese dog she's
rather fond of. ``We don't have a pet of our own.''
   Most of the customers who purchase sweets for their dogs are
women in their 30s or 40s, <LOCATION>Kashiwazaki</LOCATION> said.
   The chocolates come in both the regular brown and milky white
colors, ``contain 13 different vitamins and are made with only the
purest milk,'' according to <ORGANIZATION>Morinyu Pet Foods</ORGANIZATION>, the company that
makes them.
   Morinyu, a subsidiary of the huge <ORGANIZATION>Morinaga Milk Industry Co.</ORGANIZATION>,
<LOCATION>Ltd.</LOCATION>, began producing the chocolates six years ago, intending them
to be used as rewards given to show dogs during training.
   But <ORGANIZATION>Tokyu</ORGANIZATION>, which sells a variety of gourmet pet foods, decided
to open the pet <ORGANIZATION>Valentine</ORGANIZATION> corner because sales of the chocolates
had increased each year in mid-February, <LOCATION>Kashiwazaki</LOCATION> said.
   ``As far as I know we're the only department store doing this,''
said <PERSON>Masataka Tajima</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Tokyu</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Sales Promotions Department</ORGANIZATION>.
   Hundreds of thousands of chocolates are sold for <ORGANIZATION>Valentine</ORGANIZATION>'s Day
in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> each year. The chocolates are given by women to men, who
often return the favor on <DATE>March 14</DATE>, which is known as ``White
Chocolate Day.''
</TEXT>
