<DESCRIPT>  RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The secret's out of the bag:; These easy, mouthwatering  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A GOOD MIX  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recipes of the Week  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  homemade desserts begin; with packaged ingredients; FROZEN PEANUT BUTTER;
BANANA PIE; 1 cup cold milk; 1 package (4-serving size) instant vanilla
pudding and pie filling mix; 1/2 cup creamy or chunky peanut butter; 1 8-ounce
container frozen whipped topping, thawed (about 3 1/2 cups); 1 9-inch
chocolate crumb crust; 2 small ripe bananas;  Prepared chocolate syrup
(optional);  In medium bowl, beat milk, pudding mix and peanut butter on low
speed about 2 minutes, until smooth. Let stand 5 minutes.;   Reserve 1 cup
whipped topping; gently fold remaining topping into peanut butter mixture
until blended. Spoon 1/2 of mixture into pie crust. Slice 1 banana and arrange
over filling; top with remaining peanut butter mixture. Freeze 4 to 6 hours or
overnight.;   Before serving, swirl reserved whipped topping on pie. Slice
second banana and arrange decoratively on top. Drizzle with chocolate syrup,
if desired. Makes 8 servings.;  RASPBERRY OATMEAL BARS; 1 18.25-ounce package
yellow cake mix; 2 1/2 cups quick-cooking oats; 3/4 cup butter or margarine,
melted; 1 12-ounce jar (1 cup) raspberry, apricot, blackberry or strawberry
preserves or jam; 1 tablespoon water;  Grease 9-by-13-by-2-inch pan. In large
bowl, combine dry cake mix and oats; stir in melted butter until mixture is
crumbly. Place 1/2 of crumb mixture (about 3 cups) into pan. Press firmly to
cover bottom. Combine preserves and water; spoon over crumb mixture in pan and
spread evenly. Cover with remaining crumb mixture; pat firmly to make top
even.;   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 18 to 23 minutes; top should be
very light brown. Cool completely, then cut into bars. Store in airtight
container. Makes about 4 dozen bars.;  TRIPLE CHOCOLATE CAKE; 1 18.25-ounce
package chocolate, devil's food or Swiss chocolate cake mix or
pudding-included cake mix; 1 package (4-serving size) chocolate flavor instant
pudding and pie filling mix; 1 3/4 cups milk; 2 eggs; 1 12-ounce package
semisweet chocolate pieces;  Powdered sugar (optional);  In large bowl,
combine all ingredients except powdered sugar. Mix by hand about 2 minutes,
until well blended. Pour into greased and floured 10-inch tube or fluted tube
pan.;   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 50 to 55 minutes or until cake
springs back when lightly pressed. Do not overbake. Cool 15 minutes in pan;
remove from pan, and finish cooling on wire rack. Sprinkle with powdered
sugar, if desired.;  CHOCOLATE-FRUIT TORTE; 1 11-ounce package pie crust mix;
1 cup chocolate-flavored syrup; 1 8-ounce container frozen whipped topping,
thawed; 2 cups cut-up fresh fruit;  Mix pie crust and 2/3 cup chocolate syrup
until smooth. Spread 1/2 of mixture (1 cup) into 10-inch square on ungreased
cookie sheet. Bake in preheated 425-degree oven 6 to 8 minutes. Immediately
cut square in half to form 2 rectangles; cool 5 minutes. Remove rectangles
from cookie sheet; cool completely. Repeat with remaining mixture.;   Fold
remaining 1/3 cup chocolate syrup into whipped topping. Place 1 pastry
rectangle on serving plate. Spread 1 cup whipped topping mixture over
rectangle; top with other pastry rectangle. Repeat with remaining whipped
topping mixture and pastry rectangles. Arrange fruit around top edges. Cover
and refrigerate at least 4 hours but no longer than 36 hours. Makes 12
servings.;  DOUBLE BERRY BARS; 1 14-ounce package blueberry muffin mix; 1/4
cup packed brown sugar; 1/4 cup butter or margarine, melted; 1/2 cup seedless
red raspberry jam; 1 tablespoon lemon juice; 1 teaspoon powdered sugar; 
Grease 8-by-8-by-2-inch pan. Drain blueberries from mix; rinse with cold
water. Drain again and spread on paper towels to drain.;   For base, empty
muffin mix into medium bowl. Break up any lumps. Stir in brown sugar; drizzle
with butter. Toss with fork until crumbs form. Reserve 3/4 cup of mixture;
press remaining crumbs into bottom of prepared pan.;   For filling, combine
jam and lemon juice. Fold in blueberries. Spread over base. Sprinkle with
reserved crumbs.;   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 25 to 30 minutes or
until golden brown and jam bubbles slightly. Loosen from edge of pan; cool.
Cut into bars. Sift powdered sugar over top. Makes 32 bars.;   -- All recipes
from <PERSON>Natalie Haughton</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> Daily News;  THUMBPRINT COOKIES; 1 package
(4-serving size) any flavor instant pudding and pie filling mix; 1 10-ounce
package pie crust mix; 2 tablespoons butter or margarine, melted; 4 to 5
tablespoons cold water; 1 4-ounce package German sweet chocolate, broken into
squares;  Whole or chopped toasted nuts;  In a bowl, combine pudding mix and
pie crust mix; add butter and 4 tablespoons water. Mix with fork to form a
soft dough. (If dough is too dry, add 1 tablespoon water.) Shape dough into
1-inch balls. Place dough balls 1 inch apart on ungreased baking sheets; press
thumb deeply into center of each. Cut each square of chocolate in half. Press
1/2 into center of each cookie.;   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about 15
minutes or until lightly browned. Immediately press nuts lightly into
chocolate centers. Remove from baking sheets and cool on wire racks. Makes 3
dozen.  </TEXT>
