<DESCRIPT>  FOOD; HOLIDAY; ENTERTAINMENT; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  I USUALLY spend New Year's Eve with several close friends: First an early
dinner in our favorite Chinese restaurant, then a movie, and we're ready to
welcome the new year in a festive and frivolous mood. What could be more
elegant than returning to a gorgeously rich array of desserts and iced
champagne in the coziness of one's own home?;   Picture a table of crepes
filled with chocolate, fruits and luxurious creams. Most of the preparation
can be done ahead, so pull out all the stops and use your best china and
crystal flutes. Have the champagne chilled and an urn of coffee ready to be
poured. This will truly be a memorably sweet ending to 1991.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Food  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SWEET WAY TO RING IN NEW YEAR
RICH DESSERT CREPES CREATE SCRUMPTIOUS WELCOME FOR
1992  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Entertaining; Louise Fiszer is founder of Louise's Pantry Cooking School in
Menlo Park and author of "Season to Taste" (Simon &amp; Schuster).  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   BASIC DESSERT CREPES; 1 1/2 cups flour; 3/4 cup milk; 3/4 cup water; 3 eggs;
1 tablespoon sugar; 1 teaspoon vanilla or almond extract; 1/4 cup melted
butter; In blender or food processor, combine all ingredients until smooth.
Remove to bowl and whisk in melted butter. Let stand at room temperature at
least one hour before using.;   Brush a 7-inch pan, preferably non-stick with
a bit of butter or oil and heat until hot. Ladle about 2 tablespoons of crepe
batter into pan and swirl until surface is coated with batter. Cook 1-2
minutes until lightly browned, lift with fingers and cook briefly on other
side. Remove to plate and continue until batter is used up, brushing pan with
butter after every 3 crepes. Stack crepes with a piece of wax paper in between
each and place on flat plate. Cover and refrigerate or freeze. Bring to room
temperature before filling. Makes about 16 crepes.; (hbox); CHOCOLATE DESSERT
CREPES; 1 cup flour; 1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa; 3/4 cup milk; 3/4 cup water; 2
tablespoons sugar; 1 teaspoon vanilla or almond extract; 1/4 cup melted
butter; Proceed as directed for basic dessert crepes.; (hbox); APRICOT, WINE
AND HONEY CREPE TORTE; 1 pound dried apricots; 2 cups red wine; 6 tablespoons
honey; 12 basic dessert crepes; 2 egg whites; 5 tablespoons powdered sugar; 
Cook apricots, wine and honey on low heat about 1 hour. Let cool and puree.
Set aside. Butter a deep glass or porcelain pie dish. Lay a crepe on bottom of
dish and spread with apricot puree. Continue alternating crepes and puree
until all are used. The last crepe should not have puree on top. May be made
ahead and refrigerated at this point. Just before serving, beat egg whites
until soft peaks form. Slowly add sugar and beat until stiff. Spread meringue
on top of crepe and bake in preheated 350 degree oven until brown, about 12
minutes. Serves 6.; (hbox); CHOCOLATE CREPES WITH RUM RAISIN ICE CREAM;
Chocolate Sauce:; 8 ounces bittersweet chocolate, chopped; 1 tablespoon
instant coffee; 1/4 cup water; 2 tablespoons sugar; 2 tablespoons butter; 1/4
cup heavy cream; 8 chocolate crepes; 1 quart rum raisin ice cream; In medium
saucepan, melt chocolate with coffee, water, sugar, butter and cream. This
sauce may be made ahead and stored in covered jar in refrigerator. Fill each
crepe with about 5 tablespoons softened ice cream. Roll them and store,
covered in freezer until serving time. To assemble, heat chocolate sauce and
spoon over crepes.; (hbox); STRAWBERRY-CHEESE FILLED CREPES; Filling:; 8
ounces cottage cheese; 1/4 pound mascarpone cheese or cream cheese; 3
tablespoons sugar; 1 tablespoon grated orange zest; 1 pint strawberries,
hulled and thinly sliced; 16 dessert crepes; powdered sugar; In blender or
food processor, combine filling ingredients until smooth. Place about 2
tablespoons filling on center of crepe and top with strawberry slices. Fold
sides over and place in buttered baking dish seam side down. Continue until
crepes and filling are used up. May be made ahead to this point, covered and
refrigerated or frozen. Just before serving, sprinkle liberally with powdered
sugar and place under broiler until sugar melts, about 6 minutes.  </TEXT>
