<HEAD>School Board Bans Chocolate Milk At Lunch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEMBERTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chocolate milk, that longtime
mainstay of kids' lunches, won't be on the elementary schools' menu
come fall because the school board thinks it's unhealthy for
growing minds.
   Instead, a calcium-fortified orange drink may be offered.
   Some teachers and nurses who have expressed concern about
children having sweets at lunch requested the ban, Superintendent
<PERSON>Robert J. Moore</PERSON> said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   The panel voted 5-4 this week to discontinue selling chocolate
milk at lunch to the 4,000 pupils in the township's 10 elementary
schools.
   <PERSON>Moore</PERSON> said several school employees said they noticed children
who drank chocolate milk for lunch showed signs of hyperactivity in
the <TIME>afternoon</TIME>.
   ``Whether that's scientifically qualified, I don't know,'' <PERSON>Moore</PERSON>
said.
   Chocolate milk outsells regular milk 2-1 at <ORGANIZATION>Aletta Crichton
Elementary School</ORGANIZATION>, Principal <PERSON>Gerald L. DeClementi</PERSON> said.
   ``That's eight cases of chocolate to four cases of white a
day,'' he said.
   DeClementi said he was unaware of behavior problems that might
be tied to the chocolate milk.
   Both he and <PERSON>Moore</PERSON> said they doubt the ban will provoke an outcry.
   But if it does, school board President <PERSON>Thomas Bridge</PERSON> said the
panel could change its decision.
   Bridge, who cast the tie-breaking vote, said he was a fan of the
banished beverage.
   ``I love chocolate milk,'' Bridge said. ``But yes, there is a
lot of merit to the fact that chocolate has an effect on children.''
</TEXT>
